They were evi- dently preparing to leave Italy (Ad Div. xi. 3). Cicero, who had been for some time absent from Rome, had already set out for Greeee. On the 28th of J uly he was at Rhegium, whence he passed over to Syra- cuse. On his voyage from Syracuse he was driven back to Leucopetra, a place at the extremity of Italy, and in the neighbourhood of Rhegium. There he heard that there was a better prospect at Rome, that the recall of the Liberators was expected, that his absence was complained of, and that he was wanted (Ad Att. xvi. 7). He immediately resolved to re- turn to Rome.
